\begin_layout Subsection
Algorithm Details
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given set of SNPs associated to a single trait, SNPsea tests whether
 implicated genes, in aggregate, are enriched for specificity to an annotation
 or condition in a user-provided matrix of genes and annotations/conditions.
 The algorithm consists of three steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use linkage disequilibrium (LD) properties from reference genomes to
 identify the genes implicated by each SNP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We look up the implicated genes in a user-provided matrix and calculate
 a specificity score for each annotation/condition based on the values of
 these genes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We compare the specificity scores to scores obtained with random sets of
 matched SNP sets and use those scores to calculate an empirical p-value
 reflecting statistical significance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Assigning genes to each SNP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accurate analyses must address the critical issue that SNPs rarely implicate
 a single gene, but instead implicate a region of the genome in LD with
 0 to 20 genes that may plausibly influence the given trait (Figure 1
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "sub:FigS1"

\end_inset

).
 We determine genes implicated by each SNP using a previously described
 strategy (Figure 2
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "sub:FigS2"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rossin_proteins_2011"

\end_inset

.
 We define a linkage interval by identifying the furthest neighboring SNPs
 within a 1 Mb window with 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}>0.5$
\end_inset

 using data from reference genomes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "consortium_integrated_2012"

\end_inset

.
 Each interval is then extended to the nearest recombination hotspots with
 recombination rate >3 cM/Mb 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "myers_fine-scale_2005"

\end_inset

.
 To address the case when no genes overlap this interval, we provide an
 option to extend the interval further (by default 250 Kb) up- and downstream.
 After each SNP has been assigned to an interval and a set of genes, we
 merge SNPs with shared genes into a single locus, thereby avoiding multiple-cou
nting of a gene due to proximate user-provided SNPs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many SNP linkage intervals overlap more than one gene, as shown 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "sub:FigS1"

\end_inset

.
 We assume that one gene in each associated locus is causal and driving
 the signal of association.
 However, due to the LD structure of the genome, we expect to see many genes
 hitchhike along with the causal gene.
 The hitchhikers will be implicated by our linkage intervals due to poorly
 mapped regions in the genome, or due to regions with high LD that span
 long stretches across the chromosome.
 We tested this assumption by comparing the results of two methods using
 SNPs associated with red blood cell count (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "sub:A-single-trait-associated"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\family typewriter
'--score single'
\family default
 method (recommended) assumes that a single gene in the associated SNP's
 linkage interval is causal for the associated phenotype.
 We choose the single gene that is most likely to be affecting the phenotype
 by assuming that a gene's specificity to a cell type or tissue is a good
 substitute for the gene's importance to the function of that cell type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\family typewriter
'--score total'
\family default
 method assumes that all genes in the associated SNP's linkage interval
 are causal for the associated phenotype.
 We account for all of these genes when calculating scores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Calculating specificity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SNPsea accepts matrices with continuous or binary values in each cell, and
 a different algorithm is used to the specificity score for the two types
 of matrix.
 Before running SNPsea, a matrix with continuous values must already be
 normalized so that columns are comparable.
 
\emph on
It is not appropriate to use this method on a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

raw
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrix of expression values
\emph default
, because the values across conditions (cell types, tissues, experiments)
 will not be directly comparable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Calculating specificity for a gene expression matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\text{gene expression matrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We row-normalize a gene expression matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 genes and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 conditions by the L2 norm.
 This results in a new matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 where each value is between 0 and 1 and represents specificity of gene
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 A value of 1 indicates complete specificity to condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 0 indicates complete absence in condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 as described previously 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hu_integrating_2011"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A'_{i,j}=\dfrac{A_{i,j}}{\sqrt{A_{i,1}^{2}+A_{i,2}^{2}+\cdots+A_{i,n}^{2}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we rank each column by ascending percentile (lower rank indicates
 higher specificity) to produce a new matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A''$
\end_inset

.
 Each value is between 0 and 1 and represents a nonparametric rank of specificit
y to condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for gene 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A''_{i,j}=\dfrac{\text{Rank}(A'_{i,j})}{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each locus-condition pair, we choose the single gene with the highest
 specificity to that condition.
 To correct for testing multiple genes 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}$
\end_inset

 in each SNP locus' set of genes 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, we create a new matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of probabilities.
 It consists of one row for each SNP locus 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and one column for each condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The probabilities are corrected for testing of multiple genes present within
 each single SNP locus, because we are choosing the single gene with the
 greatest specificity among 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}$
\end_inset

 genes in each locus.
 This formula accounts for the single gene 
\family typewriter
'--score single'
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{k,j}=1-(1-\text{Min}(A''_{k,j}))^{g_{k}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also provide the option to use all genes in each SNP locus.
 This formula accounts for all genes 
\family typewriter
'--score total'
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{k,j}=-\sum_{i\in k}\text{log}_{10}A''_{i,j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Calculating specificity for a binary presence/absence matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\text{binary (1/0) presence/absence matrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We treat a matrix of genes and conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with binary values as a presence-absence matrix and do not transform it
 into 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $A''$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, we create a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of hypergeometric probabilities where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the total number of genes present in condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the number of genes in locus 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k,j}$
\end_inset

 is the number of genes from locus 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 present in condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the total number of genes in the original gene matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This formula accounts for the presence or absence of 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 (1 or more) genes in condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 
\family typewriter
'--score single'
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{k,j}=\begin{cases}
1-\dfrac{{m-m_{j} \choose g_{k}}}{{m \choose g_{k}}} & g_{k,j}>0\\
1 & g_{k,j}=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also provide the option to account for the number of genes in each SNP
 locus.
 This formula accounts for the number of genes 
\family typewriter
'--score total'
\family default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{k,j}=\dfrac{{m_{j} \choose g_{k,j}}{m-m_{j} \choose g_{k}-g_{k,j}}}{{m \choose g_{k}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, now that we have a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of probabilities, we can calculate a specificity score 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 for each condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 This formula aggregates the contributions of genes across all of the risk
 loci:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{j}=-\sum_{k}\text{log}_{10}P_{k,j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Testing significance 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each condition, we use a Monte Carlo sampling approach to calculate
 an empirical p-value that represents the probability of observing the condition
's specificity score 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 by chance.
 The specificity scores 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are obtained for a large number of random SNP sets where each SNP in the
 random set is matched to each SNP in the user's set on the number of linked
 genes.
 The random SNP sets are sampled from a list of LD-pruned SNPs that is a
 subset of the SNPs from the 1000 Genomes Project 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lango_allen_hundreds_2010"

\end_inset

.
 The exact Monte Carlo p-value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "phipson_permutation_2010"

\end_inset

 for each condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is calculated as shown below, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the number of sampled SNP sets and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the number of those sets with a specificity score greater than or equal
 to the user's score 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{j}=\dfrac{b_{j}+1}{a_{j}+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We implemented adaptive sampling, so more significant p-values are tested
 with more iterations and less significant p-values are tested with fewer
 iterations.
 Two options allow the user to control the adaptive sampling:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
'--max-iterations'
\family default
 The maximum number of iterations for each condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
'--min-observations'
\family default
 The minimum number of observed higher scores 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 required to stop sampling SNP sets for a condition 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

