\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Gene Ontology binary presence/absence matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The OBO file was downloaded from Gene Ontology (data-version: 2013-06-29,
 CVS revision: 9700): 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.geneontology.org"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each gene, we climbed the hierarchy of ontology terms, so that if a
 gene is annotated with some term 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, it is also annotated with all of the terms that are parents of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally, we used data from Homologene (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/homologene"

\end_inset

) to copy terms between homologous genes.
 For exmple, if a mouse gene is annotated with some term, and the human
 homolog is not annotated with that term, we will copy the term to the human
 gene.
 We discarded all GO terms that apply to fewer than 100 or to more than
 1000 genes.
 This left us with a matrix of 19,111 genes and 1,751 terms.
\end_layout

